election_record.label: New Hampshire 1823 Governor

overview.note: Both Levi Woodbury and Samuel Dinsmore were Republicans, however Woodbury was elected over Dinsmore, who was the regular nominee of the Republican Party. Many of the newspapers stated that a significant amount of Woodbury's vote came from the Federalists.

"The Republicans of that State have put, in nomination, two distinct Candidates before the People. One of these Candidates Mr. Dinsmoor, is supposed to be friendly to the cause of Mr. CRAWFORD, and is accordingly supported by Mr. Hill of the N.H. Patriot - The other Gentleman, Judge Woodbury is put up by some of the friends of JOHN QUINCY ADAMS, and is very ably sustained, by that valuable Paper, the New Hampshire Republican, published at Dover, N.H." New-Hampshire Gazette (Portsmouth, NH). March 10, 1823.

"It is said to be a singular fact, that a larger number of the Rockingham members, in convention, voted for Gen. Dinsmoor, than even in Cheshire County, and the Portsmouth members particularly encouraged the nomination. The fact is only important to show the utter contempt into which caucus nominations have fallen in this State. Not only no obligation is understood to be imposed; but such nominations are now regarded as a signal for extensive and determined opposition." New-hampshire Sentinel (Keene, NH). March 22, 1823.

sub_unit.name: Coventry
sub_unit.note: The votes from Coventry were not included in the Original Election Returns.

sub_unit.name: Brookline
sub_unit.note: There were no votes recorded in Brookline.

sub_unit.name: Portsmouth
sub_unit.note: "'The LITTLE Faction at Portsmouth' have thrown more votes for Levi Woodbury, than was ever before thrown for any person, for Governor, in the town. - Is it not extraordinary that this 'little faction' should give the great number of 900 votes, while the great faction, (or whatever other distinguishing appellative you may please to give them,) were only able to muster the small number of 34, including those obtained by trick?" New-Hampshire Gazette (Portsmouth, NH). March 18, 1823.
